Mission Analysis is used to define the mission need or the opportunity while characterizing the solution space and potential solution classes that could address a problem or take advantage of an opportunity. A mission describes what the system will do and the purpose of doing it. The mission statement describes Kipling’s “six honest serving-men” – who, what, when, where, why, and sometimes how (Kipling 1902). The mission provides the context for defining measures of effectiveness and for development of the Concept of Operations (ConOps) in the next phase if the mission solution is voted to move forward with development. The Mission Analysis Model provides the high level description for an application or feature. The purpose of generating the Mission Context Model early in the development process is to establish the basic needs, functions and behaviors so that systems and software level scope guardrails can be established. This mission analysis model pattern is constructed from a combination of the standard systems engineering pillars: the SEBoK, the INCOSE Handbook, and NASA's Systems Engineering Handbook. The mission analysis package contains:
  1. Problem Definition Canvas
  2. Pain Point Brainstorm & Analysis Canvas
  3. Mission Ideation
  4. Mission Context
  5. Stakeholder Analysis
  6. Mission Use Cases
  7. Functional Flow Block Diagram
